{"text": "AYE! Note to self; sailing in search of whales requires some admin skills as not to have you mates starve and try to eat each other. I will start with the general feel of the game. As I did like this game, I will start with the positive and end with the negative points I encountered.  The game was still not officially out when I played it, but I did fancy its looks and started to play it for reviewing purposes, perhaps initially more than for entertainment purposes. Although, it is important to mention that among the key things which caught my first interest is that it had steam cards, of which I am pretty fond of, as you may get and see from my profile. One is presented with a tutorial which is a bit heavy on text, but did feel guide-fully-enough and introductory to the game mechanics, or at least, for the beginning of the game and sail of with water into the ocean, and more than one crew member. Perhaps knowing that one could change the positions of the crew members of the ship would also have been helpful.  Tutorial be finished, was not that all explanatory as I had initially suspected, and one goes into the story. First impression was that I did like the way it was set out and how it was drawn. In general, the graphic work was strong and creative, drawn style, like the comics of yore sort ‘a speak. The music was inspiring and some admin decisions have to be made which are perhaps partly intuitive, but one strikes a lot of problems if one sets of on whale hunting activities, I have discovered. Also, the ambience of the harbor at starters was well thought and the sphere played along with the story and the feelings the game wanted to transmit. The learning curve may vary a bit from experience to experience. Even so, the game does look promising from the start. Not much effect, but an introduction into the game story was a lot appreciate, and I like the subject they took,  . Once one is set of with the basic sailing some questions I did not really know, and had to improvise a bit. I had no idea what it usually takes a slope to travel, say, to Honolulu from Nantucket, hence I did but too much provisions for the missions, without knowing of course that I could simply buy more in other harbors. Perhaps a glance of the map before one is set on to a mission would be a great idea. Once one is in the ocean a dreary sensation of I must have forgotten something hits you along. I have to admit a very obvious error, and that is that I set out to one missions which was a bit far away for the kind of crew, the boat you have at the start, and the lack of a steady source of income. One figures out that, as in an Role Playing Game, one will just encounter whales on the way, but that didn’t happen for me at first. I thought that with enough water and grog, I would be on my way, and some emergency situation would be rare. But I did make that mistake, and learned something about the game logic proposed. Not at all the game's fault, but would have been nice to know some more.  Than later in the game I had the option to defend a ship from pirates. Thinking that this was a beginner mission, I decided to board (not-so-smart-idea) the pirate ship, and the game mechanics in fight were not really self-intuitive. Hence, I died, and my tombstone appeared. Thank god for autosave. Then I pretty much died because I reached the very far away Honolulu as a noob, and noobs don't whale. Also, I did not find any. So, I restarted. Then I died again, because I miscalculated a more near objective. I did manage to understand the game mechanics in a fight, which I really liked, but then I got very little money for one narwhal, so I did die again, because it seems that is just what I am supposed to do in a whaling graphic adventure game.  I did have some problems at the start of the game whilst downloading on steam. It did not download the game at all but it showed installed in the library. Still it did not start nor did it actually download any files. NOTE that this was quickly resolved by a game developer when I pointed it out. They were doing some changes. Otherwise, technically I did not encounter bugs, nor did the game consume a lot of resources when it was being ran. Music, sounds, everything is pretty enjoyable.  In the end, I enjoyed the time I did spend on it. I did feel I mostly failed miserably, but the options given are nice and stimulating for one to keep playing it and finding out what it has to offer. Also, the things which occur on the ship whilst sailing and looking for whales and discovering the map where entertaining, at least for the first two hours. This makes it a complicated but overall plausible and decent game. Hence, I have mostly positive feelings about it.  I did die quite stupidly some times. Even although I hate tutorials like the next guy, I think that some parts may have been a bit misleading in the beginning. One should focus more on crew and the prestige related to it, as it seems that even though the ship one gets at the start is \"rotten\" it does to the job and helps you getting those oceanic giants.  So yeah, I could just go on and find that the admin parts are pretty key at the start of the game, and understanding the kind of crew you need when you start off. Additionally, I could probably teach you some new original ways I could die in this game, lol, but that would just be because I like experimenting some edges to see what the games lets you and does not let you do. I think it is a well thought game, with a interesting story-line which calls for more play than just an initial hour to understand it. So, I did that, and eventually I took off my whaling career, and liked the options I was offered. It will take some time investment this game, but it is worth it if you like the genre, and enjoy these kind of adventure simulations or have ever read a J. Conrad book, or another adventure situated in the 1820.  It seems to me that, if you have the time to invest, this is totally worth it. Makes it positive, at least for me.  See you in the depths of the ocean, then!", "appid": "621220", "steamid": "profiles/76561198063506736", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1516276800.0}
