{"text": "I'm a big fan of games that give you a choice and Wadjet Eye. So when their new game Unavowed came out I didn't hesitate to buy it. Very seldom do I make uninformed purchasing decisions but I've always enjoyed Wadjet's games and was excited about this simply from the trailer. In Unavowed you're playing as group of demon hunters, kinda like Ghostbusters, except for all things supernatural and without the matching jumpsuits.  While you normally play a predetermined individual in most adventure games this particular title lets you choose your character, a bit like an RPG. Although don't be fooled, the RPG similarities are few and far between. You choose your name, gender, occupation then the story plays out like any other adventure title. When you start off your character has what amounts to retrograde amnesia. As you go on different missions and your team grows you uncover more about your shrouded past. The story itself is pretty compelling and not to spoil it there are some interesting plot twists along the way. The characters you encounter are the soul of any adventure game. Even if the story is well polished I find the best games have unique characters that endear themselves to you. Unavowed was great in all aspects except one, your own character. I found myself a little bit indifferent to myself because other than the short term flashbacks alluding itself to the story I didn't feel my character grow or change in my playthrough. While the accompanying companions were all fleshed out and had multiple layers of depth mine was kinda in limbo. Aside from a few talking points related to the profession you chose at the start your character was largely determined by the way your team interacted with you. I felt like this was a missed opportunity as there's so much to draw upon even after the plot twist. I just felt the main character was parked in neutral for the entire game. Where you had pretty strong willed team members the main character felt a bit flat to me. When everyone else has pretty kickass backstories I wanted one too.  The mechanic of choosing your teammates for each case was a nice touch since each member has a different set of skills that you could use to solve the puzzles. It was the most ambitious aspect of this game that you rarely see in adventure titles and it works well. Even when you're just standing around waiting to do something it's nice listening to the idle banter between members. There were also many action sequences to keep me entertained and often tough choices at the end of each case. The puzzles were manageable and using different team members means you can solve them different ways. Nothing was too difficult you need to look up help but they weren't always glaringly simple either.  Choices were a big part of this game. None of the choices were easy or simple and I appreciated that the characters all had their own opinions on the choices I made and were even affected by them afterwards. Except you though, your character was unmoved regardless of your decisions. The consequences of which we were told we'd have to live with but I never really felt those consequences until near the end.  The story was excellent. While each of the cases you handled were self contained they all were a part of a larger picture. This made the story a lot easier to follow. If you also played the Blackwell games, one of Wadjet's earlier series you had a couple of easter eggs as this game was based in the same universe. Though you needn't play them to understand what's going on in the game. The references were subtle. New York and characters have never looked more beautiful in Adventure Game Studio and the voice acting in this game was stellar. The music was somber and set the mood very well even if the mood was pretty one note. The atmosphere was the same regardless of where your cases took you. It was rainy and dreary the entire game, even between cases back at headquarters. Despite there being different items relating to each team member in their space the areas more or less blended together. This isn't a bad thing but even during their downtime I got the feeling that there was little room for the characters to relax. Overall the game is impressive. You have a great cast of characters. Solid story, tough decisions to make, and fun puzzles. There's a bit of replay value for at least a second run through of the game. I clocked about 14 hours in my first run and I definitely enjoyed every minute of it. ", "appid": "336140", "steamid": "profiles/76561198058695291", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1535889600.0}
