{"text": "It's one of the better hack and slash games from Koei. I've been playing them since DW3. Just here to counterbalance the negative reviews of people who bought a type of game they knew they wouldn't like before playing.  PROS: Audio/Visual experience of cleaving crowds of enemies in half. the clanging of Gut's sword and the mist of blood never gets old. Lengthy story mode with lots of special missions in addition to standard exhibition mode Characters all feel different. not every hack and slash needs 40 characters. the more characters, the less they stand out. This game does not have that problem at all CONS: The AI is sometimes annoying. performing your musou and an ally officer rides his horse into you pushing you away from your enemy. Overall: 100% worth buying if its on sale, if you love Berserk, and you're a fan of musou games.", "appid": "502280", "steamid": "profiles/76561198007706278", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1577620800.0}
{"text": "The main focal point for Grand Ages: Medieval is trading and economics. You get to build roads to new cities, upgrade them so that way the caravans move faster, and to make trading that much faster. You get to build multiple resources from grain to beer to salt to meat and metal to tools. Certain resources are needed to make an item. An example being, you have to have wood to make salt and then salt to make meat. Another example could be you have to have coal and metal to make tools. You can either make a city (which is limited to four slots for a resource) to produce such resources or you can trade for them.  The actual trade business can be done a few ways. The first way is to send out someone manually and to gather resources and sell them via yourself clicking on it. The second way is to make trade routes which you can tinker with the rates, quantity, and how many cities you want along that route. This can become a fruition because that means you don’t have to deal with it, but you have to pay attention because the AI will just dump a particular resource into the market and deflate that value of the resource – this of course can be for a particular city that another AI traded with and decided to dump resources into it. Cool thing about this you can buyout or just plaster a city with more resources than they need which affects how they like you in the long run.  The AI also becomes greedy in terms of wanting more because of how much value you have. If you got 20 million coins, they want two to four million coins in order to even talk to you. I find this off putting because while I made multiple cities to become this powerful, this competitor who still only has two cities wants more money for his laziness. So to gain your losses from this off putting greed, you’d have to wait a bit more before talking to someone else. It does lower the less value you have, but I’ve seen it still reach millions even if I was in single digits (in terms of millions in coin value). The combat is okay. You build your units from the cities within a barracks and in order to make units that city has to have a barracks (that is for any and all cities you build). The interesting part about this is you have to be in a particular region to make a particular unit. If you’re in the German region you get to make Flailsman or France region you make Knights. Sieging is also lack-luster. You’ll see a bunch of trebuchets lined outside as it just brings a bunch of numbers down. No damage or such, but this isn’t a pure military game either.  A nice touch they added was ruins, treasure chests, wolves and bandits throughout the world. You can get all of this by exploring the lands with your scouts, military units or settlers – basically anything that can be controlled by you (except traders). You can raid other trade routes if at war which will give you the proceeds. You also can make your town anywhere as you please; once you have a road attached you’re go to go and can start making more income via trading resources.  You also get to have a development tree. This will help to obtain stronger units in the long run, double your output for resources, make building settlements faster, or array of other upgrades for you in the long run.  For me, the game is a nice trading sim with town management and some added war here and there. Though, it is slow for me but it does fit the casual gamer’s aspect to it; similar to Banished but less detailed on towns themselves, but more open to world trade and economics… with war and diplomacy behind it.  I did find some issues such as UI being out of place as in terms of I click diplomacy and I can’t talk to anyone unless I go to their cities. I’ve also noticed some of the achievements don’t work either. I’ve been training plenty of military troops and it doesn’t count towards it. The only campaign is the tutorial. It goes over a story about romance, betray, war, and kissing some butt. It has some nice artwork, it has voice acting, and it demonstrates to you how to play the game. It was an enjoyable experience.  I did receive this product for free and even with the tutorial it was a pleasant gaming experience. But without the tutorial experience I think the game would’ve been boring and the replayability wouldn’t appeal to me.", "appid": "310470", "steamid": "profiles/76561198003026615", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1591272000.0}
