{"text": "1993, Birmingham, England. Lester is a middle-aged forensic scientist, divorced with two kids and a tragic past. Fianna (nickname Fi) and Val are 19-year-old college students. Their disparate worlds are about to collide. When you first start the game, you can choose between light and dark versions. Both versions still deal with adult themes, but if you choose dark there will be more graphic nudity. I only played with the dark version setting, so I can’t speak to exactly how much the light version tones it down (or not). The 90s vibe is excellent and can be felt in little touches throughout the game - the overhead perspective, the menu interfaces (where you purchase items, craft spells, and view your inventory), the retro art style, and even the music has a definitive MIDI quality. There were many cool little artistic touches throughout the game. Depending on whether you’re playing Lester, Fi, or Val, the color of the hover eye changes to match the character’s eye color. I also loved that you could watch clips from classic horror films like  . And in the end credits, you can see that like many Wadjet Eye games, many of the game locations have been inspired by real places in Birmingham. There does seem to be a minor bug in that the Steam Community stuff and achievements that pop up in the bottom right corner never fully disappear. It wasn’t enough to really bother me, but it did distract a little from the immersion. The spellcrafting is an interesting mechanic because you must find both the ingredients and the apparatus as well as figure out which puzzle each spell would be useful for. There is also a lot of the traditional crime-solving aspects of hunting down leads and clues. One fun thing is that it’s given a more real investigation feel in that there are dead ends - not every clue and lead goes somewhere. In terms of story, there are pros and cons to not being able to pick up items until you need it. Sometimes in this particular game I think it felt a little more like a con because there was a lot of stuff to click on that never does anything in the game at all (e.g., chairs and benches that your character always says they have no time to sit in). The inventory was also a little clunky. Also, there wasn’t any real way to know if you were totally done at a location since they often didn’t disappear from the map even if there was nothing else to do there the rest of the game. This meant there was almost an onerous amount of stuff to double-check if you got stuck and hadn’t picked up the right item yet. The journal was not particularly helpful in this regard, and as far as I could tell, there wasn’t really a good way to get a hint if you were stuck. Although the game is marketed as having multiple choices that affect the possible endings, there are really only two places where the character makes deviation choices. Everything else along the way doesn’t really have an impact. I believe there are 5 possible endings. One thing that was cool is that the end credits song is different depending on which ending is chosen. Once you complete the game for the first time, the Bonus Chapter is unlocked in the credits in a really hilarious breaking of the fourth wall. Your ending choice in the main game does affect the dialogue in the game. It’s short but fun, hints at the larger universe, and has some really awesome Christmas song remixes. For the quality and length of the game, the $5 price seems very reasonable when compared against similar games and their prices. Despite its flaws, this game had a very enjoyable story and puzzles, and I would love to revisit these characters again if another game were made. At any rate, I immediately sought out other games from the developer, if that lets you know how I liked it.", "appid": "1074520", "steamid": "profiles/76561198032373667", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "36", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1566648000.0}
{"text": "All these memes were attracting me the whole time from game release and here I am, it is January of 2019 and I decided to check this game with outdated graphics.  I was thinking it is very short game for 5 hours or something, but turned out this game caught up me for 15 hours. You can finish this game much earlier, but if you want to explore everything, it really can take some time. This game make you laugh, this game make you cry, it can make you regret for some of your decisions. I haven't seen such emotionally driven game for a long time. This game tells a great story, what is more important YOU are the one who creates the story, there are a lot of decisions that can change the outcome for each character in the game. One of the best indie games of this decade! Go try it, you won't regret!", "appid": "391540", "steamid": "profiles/76561198022354259", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1546862400.0}
