{"text": "Call of Pripyat. So far the latest of the STALKER games, the most technically advanced one, with the best visuals out of three games, and the best choice of mods. But let's say you're still new to the whole thing. Maybe you've started playing FPS games by the time when Far Cry 3 (4? 5?!) was released. Even then you have probably heard of this game somewhere. Because it's not some fun show with the hats, brave heroes, and sporadic explosions from time to time. Some people even call STALKER \"the most immersive video game series ever made\". So it's not just a linear run-and-gun show, but what's with that? Why there are so many positive reviews on the whole serial? Well, it's the atmosphere in the game, as simple as that. And we both know that 90% of the time when you see something about the \"atmosphere\" in some game, it means nothing. Seriously, when you hear about those \"very atmospheric\" AAA titles, you know that the reviewer was most certainly aimed to say at least something positive about the game without saying anything in particular. Not the STALKER case. You see, the typical FPS games are mostly constructed around the visual part. Sometimes you're allowed to kill something with the nice soundtrack, but generally, it's all about the eyes show. Now, proper horror games are often going with some very basic visuals but taking some time with making you quite uneasy with the ambient sounds. All those scratches, whispers and the sudden wind blows out of nowhere are really twitching the nerves, if played right. However, horror games are usually making the player quite defenseless and mindless in his efforts. Now, STALKER is a horror game that gives you the proper reasons to go into some abandoned structures, filled with monsters and anomalies. And of course, it gives you the means to come out of it. Some chances to see another day after some interview with a vampire or a poltergeist. STALKER makes you a survivor. A hunter. Always hungry, always lacking ammo (there is never a lot of ammo: either it's Way too little, or it's just not enough, but you simply can't carry any more). STALKER makes you an adventurer, looking into every corner for some hidden stash with the goods that will make your life a bit easier. STALKER expects the player to use all standard movement keys and tricks, including usually useless left-right bends, to move in and out of some obstacles, and to find something shiny on the way. If you can't jump or climb somewhere in one move there, it doesn't mean it's impossible. Take a train as an example: to reach the roof, you jump on the coupling part first, then on the railings around the driver's cab, and then you can reach the lowest point of the roof from there. What you'll find up there is another question. Could be nothing. Could be a couple of medkits. Or a rare VSS or SVD rifle... You never know! Unless you're the guide's guido or the best Google's friend. So, the STALKER game make some things to you. It is disappointing you from the start with the lack of proper instructions we're all so care about... You know, \"press WASD to move, SPACE to jump, \"6\" and \"O\" to check for anomalies\" - all that usual trainy day stuff. It is lacking some \"save the day\" main quest - yeah, even the Call of Pripyat, the most streamlined of the STALKER games, is very far from pushing you somewhere. Just walk around, you know? Talk to people, some of them can give you hints or even quests. Look for some loot and please, please, mind to gear up before you'll enter the firefight! Oh, and remember about monsters and anomalies all around! They are not that bad, usually, unless you come too close. But you can learn that \"too close\" point only from the experience. So the STALKER game makes you a researcher type! The type that takes the probes on the not-so-solid ground, and learning everything from the personal touch. STALKER, by any means, is not your typical FPS game. You don't need to kill a lot. You can, of course, but if you're a trigger-happy type, there are much better shooter games. On the other hand, the game's unique vibe is second to no other. Even today, in late 2020, more than 10 years after the release. So please, give it a try! Mark is 9/10. Could certainly have more of that stuff: more guns, more locations, more chained quests with unclear entry points and outcomes. As grim as it looks like now, the STALKER games (especially the   and Call of Pripyat) are certainly the very bright spots in so many players' lives. Join the club!", "appid": "41700", "steamid": "profiles/76561198112810429", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "84", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603454400.0}
