{"text": "🔸I do enjoy a good action/survival horror but as for the psychological category, I only go for them when they're either highly-acclaimed or a friend's recommendation.   succeeds at jangling your nerves and never letting you settle. However, some palpable design issues invalidate what it accomplishes at first. You control Dwayne, a man who has committed an unspeakable act and is now being tormented by ghostly visions of the previous tenants of his house. Through the four chapters of  , He must follow clues and solve puzzles to escape the house, all while maintaining his sanity and trying to stay alive.  starts with a wholly disturbing and unsettling violence cutscene, lasting long enough to make an apathetic player like me feel uneasy. So bear that in mind when playing the game. You begin in an enormous house without a real sense of what is happening. The house in this state serves as a hub between the real and the surreal world. You'll be able to familiarize yourself with its basic layout in this state and save items such as lighters and pills into your inventory before setting out on unrelenting journeys. Atmosphere is undoubtedly the most notable point in  . The environment itself is nothing groundbreaking; A large house that feels bland at first but as you progress through each chapter, it fascinates you more and more with its ever-changing design. Each chapter focuses on recounting mental health and the debilitating effects of illnesses' of those who previously inhabited the house. Each arc tells a tale with a satisfying and gruesome ending that conveys the world that you’ve stumbled on. While they can be played in any order, Lucy's chapter servers as a prologue with its easier puzzles and forgiving moments. The next one, Dolores's chapter is the closest to what the game should've been. From there, it starts to falter in pacing and faithfulness to its original design that it feels utterly rushed and broken. You often find yourself retracing the corridors with a somewhat slowed pace. The game heavily relies on investigating the house and solving environmental puzzles which in return, dynamically changes its layout based on your progress or collected items. The jump scares and puzzles are laid out discreetly throughout the first two chapters, though, the second half becomes more of a cutscene mania with some cat-and-mouse games in between. Along the way, light sources and pills keep your sanity high. Consumables are limited resources, and you’re encouraged to be sparing with your stock as the house messes with your mind by slamming doors and shutting off lights. Let your sanity decrease too fast, and you’re likely to get a visit from something much worse than some muffled footsteps or a fleeting face. Although, the real terror comes in when you have to use the inventory. Attempting to set candles down, arrange your inventory, or do anything with your items is often annoying due to clunky controls that could've been easily avoided by setting some hotkeys. Throughout the game, there are scripted encounters with the villains when they just toy with you. In a game like this, if the villain has the opportunity to kill you and chooses not to, all the tension and scares that led to this point is lost. There are numerous encounters when they catch and supposedly kill you. But it's just a cheap gimmick used to excuse teleporting you somewhere else to progress through the story. It only nullifies the fear factor and eliminates the jump scares. Regrettably, unlike Dolores's chapter where you can mostly finish objectives in the order you want, you're constantly expected to follow the villain's footstep that often results in finding solutions before the problem is created. The linearity could've been improved if it was given a little of RNG spice.  creates a palpable playground for fans of horror to revel in, varying in different locations from lost treehouses to grim cemeteries and psychiatric facilities that offer an unnerving and mystifying experience. The level design is on top of the line here, to say the least. Lightning effects are the blessing and the curse of the game. While it's been used effectively to create a grisly atmosphere, some areas are pitch dark without the slightest reflection while the light source is only a few inches away. This is a known issue when no light source points are specified in an area in Unreal Engine. Another horrendous draw-back is character models. They're often encountered remotely or in shadows, though, when you get a glimpse of them they are despicably unpolished. Audio design is just as effective as everything else in shaping its terrifying atmosphere.   does a superb job of layering rain, creaks, moans, muffled footsteps, and radio static to make this a constant threatening soundscape. The use of headphones is highly recommended. 🔸 🔸 The game runs with all settings set to the lowest, using about 80% of VRAM at 1050p 30 FPS. 🔸 🔸 🔸Visage is slow-paced and unforgiving. Puzzles and exploration rely on a trial-and-error basis for the entirety of the game. This approach succeeds at delivering a horrifying setting early on but degrades to a cat-and-mouse game in the second half which isn't something the game was aiming for. Looking past some of the severe game design and technical issues,   often creates a gruesome atmosphere accompanied by disturbing and unsettling imageries that appeal to true psychological horror fans. 🔸There's not much to accomplish once the game is finished. However, completionists are in for a treat. Most of the lore is told via collectibles in the forms of comic books, VHS, and cassette tapes. The current base price is $35 which in my opinion is high, given there's a handful of game-breaking bugs and no ETA is given for fixing them.", "appid": "594330", "steamid": "profiles/76561198200879134", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "27", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1606219200.0}
