{"text": "Dying Light has gone a long way to fix some of the problems that troubled Dead Island, its predecessor. Dead Island had problems but it also held promise as a ‘first-person open world zombie slayer' years before such games appeared everywhere.  Dying Light fixes issues such as over-powered zombies that are almost impossible to kill with low-level weapons--instead, Zombies have the same attributes throughout the game. Second, unlike Dead Island's generic experience point mechanic which was the basis for its skill system, in Dying Light the player feels involved in their character's progress as they 'learn' skills in different skill trees, such as acquiring new parkour techniques or being able to crush skulls. By helping other survivors, you unlock progressively more powerful crafting recipes and survivor skills.  It almost feels like you are learning alongside Crane. The progression system encourages different types of play while giving players the freedom to engage with the game as they choose. Nothing is stopping you from using the myriad guns that are left around Harran, but shooting enemies provides almost no experience points and the loud shots attract unwanted attention.  The real standout in Dying Light is of course the parkour mechanic, which is used to give the player a sense of motion that is unparalleled by any other game. Running through the city feels like rapid acceleration in a sports car. Vaulting over walls and scrambling up to rooftops feels triumphant. Navigating a narrow ledge on the top of a communications tower feels terrifying. Parkour is meant to be improvisational, which is the feeling that you get in Dying Light--traversing in the environment with fluidity and grace.  The game's multiplayer component works great! Up to three additional players can cooperatively deal with zombie hordes. Besides, this mode also encourages friendly competition, such as timing how fast checkpoints are reached, or seeing who can kill the most zombies or find the most loot in a set amount of time. There's also asymmetrical PVP, wherein a player takes on the role of a super-powered zombie hunting down a team who is tasked with destroying a series of zombie nests.  Some have commented that the story is the weakest point of Dying Light. But where the writing does impress is in its character moments and philosophical depth. A good number of characters express opinions about the end of the world that are worth listening to. Those conversations go into aspects of survivor guilt, the meaning of sacrifice, and the question of proper social construction. From beginning to end, Dying Light is a great experience. The combat is truly satisfying, the parkour is fully realized, and the game takes place in an environment perfectly designed for the game's strengths. For all of its problems, Dead Island was pointing towards something great in the future -- Dying Light is the game that Dead Island wanted to be. Moreover, it has grown past its roots and become an incredible masterpiece in its own right.", "appid": "239140", "steamid": "profiles/76561198001782126", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "46", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1592136000.0}
{"text": "Qué tiempos los del Hitman Blood Money, cuando al sacar el rifle del maletín, el pelado iba y lo armaba parte por parte, y al guardarlo lo desarmaba como correspondía. O cuando al terminar una misión había noticias relativas a la misma relatando los hechos y sus consecuencias, y que variaban según tus acciones. O cuando podías personalizar las armas a gusto con la paga de tus misiones. Hasta tenías un nivel de notoriedad, y el cómo realizaras una misión podía influir en las próximas (lo que podía ser un poco rompe pelotas pero podías incluso pagar \"servicios\" para reducir dicha notoriedad). Son cosas que considero hicieron a ese juego el mejor de la saga. Hoy al parecer cuesta más cuidar los pequeños detalles incluso con grandes motores gráficos. >>Pero al pelado lo banco y como juego de sigilo cumple su cometido. Tiene contenido de sobra y si tenías la versión del 2016 te permite agregar todas sus misiones remasterizadas, obviamente sin pagar de más. Lo que es la \"historia\" ya no parece tener relevancia, pero nunca me importó mucho realmente. Los gráficos están joya, y sin duda es mucho mejor juego de lo que fue el Absolution.", "appid": "863550", "steamid": "profiles/76561198094600389", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1562760000.0}
