{"text": "Tom Clancy's The Division is a frustratingly good game. Everyone who's come back to the game after a long break unanimously rates it very highly. A lot of bugs and issues that plagued it early on have been fixed. In my case, I am a new player, joining in over the Steam Winter Sale, and I am impressed with it. It is an RPG Loot shooter. You play a regular citizen of New York who is a secretly trained as an agent to be activated only in times of desperate need. A viral outbreak in the city has left it in a huge mess and mostly cut from the world, so you are activated. You start your deployment as a second-wave agent after the first wave fails. The Division is an RPG first, and a shooter second. I can't stress that enough. This means that enemies (especially bosses) have big health pools which you must bring down. Do not play the game expecting it to have shooter mechanics like Call of Duty. I think many of the reviews complaining about the bullet sponge enemies have failed to understand that about the game. Anything less than a high-end, sniper will not kill an enemy on a single head shot; and it will never 1-shot a boss or elite. You are constantly on the hunt for better loot (gear) to be better at turning enemies into carbonara. Once you reach end-game at level 30, your activities all become about getting better loot except for collecting the audio logs and hidden secrets spread across the map. It is those audio logs and scattered messages that pain the grim reality of those who lived in the city during the outbreak. The city really comes alive as you explore the now abandoned buildings and apartments, stores and car garages; NYC is frozen in time. The environment design is amazing. There's painstaking detail down every street and alley, and it makes for a great place to explore. Having never been to NYC, I can't speak for its accuracy, but it definitely captures the feel. Weapons all sound distinct and powerful even when equipped with suppressors. Explosions and abilities sound adequate along with your watch's AI voice constantly giving you situational updates. The voice acting ranges from really good, to annoying. Most audio logs are good, but others are downright cheesy. Enemies communicate with each other and taunt you during fights. The voice acting there is generally good but can be repetitive. Some of the NPCs who give out missions have... interesting personalities, which while funny, really break immersion. It has a really good game engine which renders lots of objects and cars all over the streets to seek cover during firefights. There is some destruction but not too much, only ambience. Firefights can produce all sorts of fire, explosions and mayhem which the engine tends to take in stride and without lag. The standard graphic quality options are there if you start to get slowdowns, but for some reason there are a few that you cannot turn off, just lower the quality. This can leave slower PCs with sharp objects and effects on the screen, but blurry textures. I definitely recommend a mid-to-high end PC to really enjoy the game at higher settings. NYC is divided in districts/neighborhoods, each with a safehouse with a NPC contact for missions. Side-mission give a good bit of XP and crafting recipes. The shorter \"Encounters\" will award with much less XP, but will give you Security, Tech, or Medical resources. You use these to unlock parts of respective wings at you Base of Operations. Each area you unlock is tied to the perks and abilities you have. You can potentially ignore it, but it will make the game much harder. You'll mainly have 2 ability slots to equip at any time, ranging from healing stations and sensor pulse, to deployable turrets, cover shields, and seeking grenades. You can change them at any time, even in a fight (as long as it is not on cooldown). This allows you to try different loadouts and perks to find what works best for you and the situation. You'll also have 2 weapons and a sidearm slot with tons of choices between shotguns, assault rifles, sniper rifles, and SMGs; too many options to list. Weapons can be modified with scopes, lasers, grips and other \"mods\" giving each additional bonus. Higher level weapons also have talents further diversifying your loadout. The main story missions are also scattered around the map. Just like the side missions, you can play them in any order so long as you are the right level. Completing each will award a big chunk of one of the 3 resources for you Base of Operations. Every mission can be played alone or with up to 3 friends. You do not have to have a friend with you, but it helps. I have made it to level 30 alone just fine, although some firefights took more tries and were more difficult alone. Bringing friends means someone can revive you if you go down, can help you flank, and won't even take your loot. Each player gets their own loot drops. If planning to play in a group, note that the enemies will scale up to the highest level character.  A group is almost a necessity when entering the Dark Zone. The Dark Zone is a world PvP area covering a large portion in the middle of the map. All enemies that roam the area are elites, or bosses. Not only do you have harder enemies, but you have other potential players who could kill you for your loot. Fortunately or not (depending on your take on PvP) going \"Rogue\" incurs some penalties if you get killed. If you kill enough players, a mission will trigger to have the other players hunt you down. It's an interesting mechanic but not very well implemented in favor of less griefing. It would be easier to steal loot if you could just take it and go. However to pull items out of the dark zone, you must take them to an extraction area and call from a helicopter. This will notify both enemies and players that you have stuff you are extracting. You have to hold down and then place your \"infected\" loot on a rope. It is a lot of hectic fun and you get good loot here, but it is best played in a full team. There are also other events and areas to clear in the dark zone, which is itself divided in zones of increasing difficulty. Go north for better loot, but tougher enemies and competition. You do not have to go in the Dark Zone at all if you do not want to. You don't even gain XP there, as you have a separate \"Dark Zone Level\" to gain. You can still get loot from just killing enemies in the world or doing other PvE content. At level 30 the map spawns some events as you travel around. You can hunt down \"High Value Targets,\" complete daily and crafting challenges, replay story missions on higher difficulties, or play content from the DLC.  - DLC: Underground gives you random PvE missions in the NYC subways,  - DLC: Survival has you stripped of gear and fighting to overcome hunger and the environment as well as enemies to survive and extract out. Can be played PvE or PvP - DLC: Last Stand is a new objective-based 8v8 game in the dark zone - Resistance is a PvE mode where you fight waves of enemies - Incursions are tougher PvE missions to take down bosses of enemy factions. Essentially a raid - Skirmish gives you smaller maps for team-based PvP akin to what you'd find in other game's deathmatch modes All in all, there is a lot to do alone, or grouped. Come to the game expecting a RPG and you won’t be disappointed by the spongy enemies. Come with that loot hunting mentality and you won't find it a grind. It is not too far from Diablo or Borderlands in that regard. Come with friends and it will be even better.", "appid": "365590", "steamid": "profiles/76561197999875905", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "116", "votes_funny": "4", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1515931200.0}
