{"text": "### sehr wenig stunden für eine Review gespielt? Nein, die Titel wurden meist auf anderen Plattformen/Accounts ausgibig getestet ### Zusammenfassung: Grafik\t\t+ Story\t\t        +- Syncro\t\t++ Gameplay\t        + Details: Ich widme mich diesem Spiel bewusst erst jetzt. (Februar 2014) Der Hype, der um das Game gemacht wurde, war mich mehr als abschreckend. Nun also eine kleine Review: Was wohl der haupt-\"nicht-kauf“-grund der meisten Leute ist und war, welche sich für das Spiel interessierten, ist der grafik-styl/Look. Ich muss gestehen, dass es mir zu Anfang auch so ging, jedoch wurde ich schnell eines besseren belehrt! Nach den ersten 30 min fällt er einem nicht mehr auf oder anders gesagt alles ist in sich stimmig und macht die Spielwelt dadurch glaubhaft. Zudem kann ich die Entscheidung im Nachhinein auch für die Hardwareanforderungen gut heißen, da das Spiel durchgängig flüssig (auf modernen Systemen (und ich rede nicht von unter 60fps oder gar 30fps)) läuft. Dies wäre wohl mit einer anderen Engine nur schwer machbar gewesen. Der nächste Punkt ist die Story. Dazu muss ich sagen, dass sich die Arkane Studios in meinen Augen ein Eigentor geschossen haben. Die Gesichter wurden so gut auf ihre Rolle im Spiel hin modelliert, sodass man von Anfang an merkt, dass etwas nicht stimmt. Nichtsdestotrotz ist die Story sehr schön erzählt, was auch der sehr guten DEUTSCHEN Syncro zu schulden ist! Wer jedoch die ganze Geschichte erleben will und wirklich alle sich stellenden fragen geklärt haben will, sollte zur GOTY greifen. Zum eigentlichen Gameplay: mir ist aufgefallen das man, wenn man erst einmal einen für seine Spielweise (stealth/fight) passende Combo der Spezialkräfte gefunden hat immer nach diesem Schema vor geht und 90 % des Spiels so durchzieht. In den restlichen 10 % kam es mir so vor, als ob der Entwickler mich zwingen wollte, diese eine Fähigkeit zu nutzen, da es sonst übertrieben aufwendig wurde voran zu kommen. Bleibt zum Schluss zu sagen Dishonored macht spaß, weil es eben nicht nur fight/stealth/story/grafik ist, sondern eine sehr gute Mischung aus all dem.", "appid": "205100", "steamid": "profiles/76561198012924989", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1394366400.0}
{"text": "I seriously have a love/hate relationship with this game. On the one hand, it has a great and compelling story, good dialogue, and an art style and overall aesthetic I adore. And that's to say nothing of the music, sound effects, and voice acting, which are all top notch. I think I could listen to that mournful cello track from here to eternity, which is probably good because that's about how much you'll hear it when prowling the streets of plague-ridden London. I also think the combat is much better than many people seem to think. I like the whole   vibe, but I hate games that punish me so much for a simple screw up or missing one combo. With most souls-like games, you're basically screwed and starting over with zero \"XP\" (I know it's souls in their currency, but work with me here) from your last bonfire (check point). In contrast,   is probably the most gentle and forgiving souls-like game I've played, insofar as you do lose progress from your last check point, but the check points are much more liberal. One of the bones I'd pick with the title is actually that I have no bloody idea when the game saves. The only way I'm certain it saves is if I find a hideout and sleep, but then of course that advances to the next night and updates all the districts. I don't always want to do that, but I'll be damned if I've figured out in my nearly 20 hours of play when it actually saves. Sometimes it seems like it saves the last time I opened a door, other times it seems like it saved two hours ago. I don't get it. Another minor complaint is that the game does a positively   job of telling you what you're doing and why you care. Seriously, it's obvious you're a vampire--if that's a spoiler, you're too dumb to play, sorry--and the game makes it clear how several of the mechanics work. It teaches you how to pick weapons, open your inventory, and perform minimally in combat. What it doesn't do at all is tell you about the two most important mechanics in the game: (1) taking care of districts, and (2) your choice to heal or eat the surrounding populace. Every other vampire-themed game I've played has had NPCs significant to the story. I usually know that they are because I can't kill them. The best of the breed let me kill them anyway, but cause me to lose out on side quests and things they can do for me if I choose to eat them. I knew   was all about NPCs having social circles and thus bearing greater responsibility for my decisions, but I didn't realize it was basically an all-or-nothing proposition. As many reviewers/guides have observed, if you choose to embrace (read: drink dry) even   person in a district, the whole thing starts to go to hell very quickly. There's very little tolerance for error here. That wouldn't be so bad if the game made it clear how the district mechanics work, but it tells you next to nothing about it. And the amount of XP and progress you can make without eating people pales by comparison to the quick reward of draining somebody dry. You essentially have a choice: eat a person or two and consign the whole district to a sad and desolate hellscape of death and chaos, or choose to play the good guy and spend all your time grinding painfully. I wish I'd known that going into it. I also   the map. I don't know how, but it is literally the WORST map I have ever used in an RPG game. I'm nearly 20 hours into the game, and I don't have a clue how the map works. The areas that look like I can traverse them aren't. The areas that look like I can't traverse them are open. Sometimes. And no matter what I do, the bloody icon indicating my position turns in random directions every time I open the damned map. It's a bloody chore and frustrating as hell just to figure out how the hell to get to the thing that's right next to me. I'm also sorry to say the variety of weapons and skills isn't great. There's quite a number of different weapons you can use, but they all seem pretty lame. There's a whole upgrade mechanic to improve them, and they do get better, but at no point have I felt like I'm wielding an awesome weapon. I always feel like I'm chipping away at ever-scaling enemies with a slightly improved toothpick compared to the last toothpick I was using. When it comes to the skills, the upgrade trees are  , but it's clear I'm never going to see more than the tiniest fraction of it. The skills cost so much to upgrade, and you're going to be struggling to earn enough XP just to buy the most essential things, that you're never going to see anything upgraded much within the game. Several of them strike me as fiddly and/or useless too: throwing up barriers that don't last, \"coagulating\" enemy blood to stun them, or pumping tons of XP into your healing ability that just isn't worth it. At no point have I yet felt like a big, bad scary vampire, and that's sad: the power fantasy is one of the big reasons to play such games in the first place. But more than anything what irritates me most about the game is the way it punishes you without warning. You can walk through the same city street a thousand times and face only low-level foes tuned to your level. But after you trigger story event X, the next time you walk through that same street you'll be confronted with a mini-boss the like of which you've never seen before. And he'll kill you damned near instantly and leave you stuck there facing him down again to make any progress, only when you respawn you have no blood and lousy prospects for obtaining any with him right in front of you. The first one of those was bad enough, a guy who suddenly whips out a cross and wields a two-handed weapon that kills me in two hits. But the second was bloody ridiculous. I finally made it to chapter two after over a dozen-plus hours of grinding--again, I'm playing as the \"good guy\", so I get like 5 XP for every bad dude I kill and 25 XP for every citizen I heal compared to the THOUSANDS I'd get for drinking even the lowest-value NPC--and my \"reward\" was to walk out and immediately face down the Thanos and Galactus combo. Ok, they weren't actually that tough, but the ever-spawning minions were. When I met them, there was also a guy who shot flaming crossbow bolts and two guys with torches. I carefully took out the guys with torches one at a time, and they respawned. I then carefully took out the guy with the crossbow and he respawned. Over the course of the next 15+ minutes of fighting, I think I killed at least two-dozen-plus more respawning crossbow/torch enemies, and they just kept respawning! So I tried focusing on the big bad guys instead, only the big one two-shots me and seems basically impervious to every form of damage I can do. My best melee hits seemed to do the most damage, taking down his health by about 0.1%. Maybe if I could survive his four buddies for a few   I could kill him. But I can't, given their constant throwing of grenades, shooting flaming crossbow bolts, etc. I   stupid garbage like that. The game doesn't open up new tools for you and give you new fun ways to play, it punishes you instead over and over for your every success. Despite all that, I keep going back to the game. I want to finish it. I love the situation, I love the presentation values, I'm hooked into the story, and playing a \"good guy\" vampire against type is fun despite the horrible grind. Many of the fights are enjoyable, just not the surprise-mini-boss versions. I'm having a damned hard time getting past the warts and stupid let's-punish-the-player-now garbage that pops up after every story decision. I'm going to recommend the game on the whole to anyone who likes vampire-themed games, but be warned: it has a whole lot of bad along with the good.", "appid": "427290", "steamid": "profiles/76561197965466830", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1590667200.0}
