{"text": "A definitive work of great care and brilliant art that touches upon the taboo subject matter of severe mental illness delivering a story and an experience that is destined for cult greatness - Hellblade: Senua's Sacrifice. And right off the bat lets’ applaud the stellar performance by Melina Juergens playing the role of Senua, a Pict warrior from Orkney and our titular heroine. Melina really infuses life into the character of Senua through her dialogue delivery and makes you feel the torment of going through game's quest. She is to this game what Uma Thurman is to Kill Bill - a perfect fit. The technical team has also done an amazing job at capturing the emotions Senua conveys throughout the playthrough. In a way the game starts somewhat abruptly as Senua is already on her way to find Hela with the reasons and motivations for the same coming through the story deeper into the game. But this awe-inspiring masterpiece is actually a brilliant depiction of psychosis, a condition that our troubled protagonist suffers from and has been visualized tastefully into this hack 'n' slash + puzzle solver hybrid game by Ninja Theory. The narration is driven by the voices in Senua's mind that are always vying for her peace along with some other characters that Senua, in a way, encounters during her journey. I say 'in a way' because there isn't actually anyone else except Senua and her horrors traversing the lands of this game and everyone else that she encounters (who are not hostiles) only exist in their ethereal forms. Each of the characters' dialogue delivery has been done with beautiful and apt dramatics to add to the emotional journey of Senua's road to Hel. There is a lot to feel in Senua's quest for the player and it will leave a lasting impact in your mind in a way only stories within video games can. What is also without question is the legendary sound design of this game. Listen to me, don't play ANY other game with headphones but playing this with headsets (with a good bass) immensely elevates the experience of Hellblade and couples extremely well with the theme of the game. The well performed voice acting is actually only one component of Hellblade's oratory excellence - everything from the atmospheric effects to music come together to define Senua's psychosis driven world. Graphics and level design also need lauding and the game is largely linear but often given the illusion of being open world. This I feel was a good decision once again for the narrative of the game.  The combat is not excessively deep though personally I thoroughly enjoyed the swordplay and felt there was adequate action in my 10-hour spell in the game (played on Hard). The slow-motion reflexes and character battle animation have good finesse and there is enough of a challenge there for most gamers who into linear story-based experiences. There puzzles are unique and again in the frequency of what the developers want to depict through their story of a warrior battling with her inner demons and at the same time using her inner focus to combine disjointed paths to progress - the puzzles themselves are quite unique in their representation and I'm not sure if I have encountered anything like it before. It all just makes so much sense for what the game is attempting to achieve in its visualizations. Ditto with the enemies and bosses that are satisfying in their design and challenge.  One can only be excited about what other projects do Ninja Theory lined up after the level of talent and respect they have put into Hellblade. There is always a good time to play this though it is exactly the kind of experience you are looking for over a weekend of playthrough. And it's a masterpiece. The achievement of this game is palatable within the first few minutes of gameplay and only builds on itself as you move ahead, to Hel. 9/10", "appid": "414340", "steamid": "profiles/76561198061419773", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1591531200.0}
