{"text": "Honnêtement, j'aurais voulu laisser une note positive du jeu mais je ne peux point^^, vu le nombre de choses négatives à signaler dans ce  -Jeu beaucoup trop court ( +/- 5 heures de jeu ) par rapport au premier opus  ( +/- 15 heures de jeu ) et donc, je constate que   pour   dooonc WTF?^^ -Pourquoi avoir changé la vue des combats, ça n'a pas de sens !! ... Même si c'est pour ce côté hentaï très immature (qui n'apporte rien au jeu), j'ai trouvé ça très nul d'avoir constamment des personnages qui essaient de tirer des tronches moe-moe qui font pleurer de rire les ados. En plus, soit dit en passant, le choix visuel des personnages pour le père et la mère du héros (Edge) est un peeeeeu zarbi : La mère et le père ont l'air aussi jeunes que leur fiston^^. -Où sont les quêtes qu'il y avait dans le 1 et à quoi ont servi les items récupéré dans le 1 ???  et on est en pilote semi-automatique durant les 3/4 du jeu, pendant tout le scénario ! Ainsi doonc, ben on n'apprend rien de ce qu'on devait logiquement apprendre en collectant des items qui manquaient en ayant fini l'opus 1. -Je trouve que si c'était juste pour faire une fin plausible au jeu ou qui ne soit pas frustrante pour les joueurs, ça n'était pas utile de mettre ça dans un opus si court; ou mieux, ça aurait été plus logique de le mettre dans le 1 et, par la suite dans le deux,   ou   mais avec de nouvelles quêtes et obtenir un deuxième jeu complet plutôt que d'avoir créé juste une fin de jeu qui était prévue mais  Bref, en conclusion,   était sympa et prometteur tandis que   est trop court et pas suffisamment abouti, pour ne pas dire brouillon, même si la fin du jeu est assez plausible.Dommage  ... Dommage aussi pour la traduction en français, ça n'aurait pas pris beaucoup de temps, je pense.", "appid": "569970", "steamid": "profiles/76561198812185516", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "12", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1559390400.0}
{"text": "TL;DR: I'd appreciate this game a lot more if it allowed itself to be a more passive experience, but it really doesn't. While NGU IDLE is a well enough put together production, I don't particularly recommend it on the basis that, for an idle game, it demands entirely   management from the player. My time spent in this is largely in spite of myself because the \"ha ha numbers go up\" part of my idiot lizard brain is very hard to turn off sometimes. After 18 hours over one weekend I've had to uninstall it for my own sake. Take for comparison Cookie Clicker, which while not entirely the inception of the genre, certainly popularized it: it's possible to invest a   into minmaxing it. But once you have an initial setup it's something you can check in on occasionally, buy some new buildings, and simply ascend when it starts slowing down. With a few ascensions under your belt, you can crank out a starting setup in under 10 minutes and get on with your day, maybe keeping it in the background for when golden cookies show up, maybe just checking in every few days or so. A very passive experience. NGU Idle is not content with just being an idle game, ironically enough. Aside from the lion's share of the interface resembling an Excel spreadsheet with well-chosen tones of blue, there are systems on top of systems on top of systems which are admirably   against each other, but each require their own management. First you need to slot energy into training, which is its own mire of intricacies. You'll probably want to split it evenly between attack and defense, which means clicking on the button to assign a value of half the current idle energy (but not half the energy cap!), then click on the + next to each of the skills you want to train. Unless the energy you're assigning goes over the skill's current max efficiency cap, in which case you want to hit the 'cap' buttons instead. Why is it even possible to assign more energy to skills than you can actually make use of in the first place?! Then once that's sorted you fight bosses with your new stats; then you unlock adventure mode, which is a game within a game that has very similar attack/defense stats, but entirely separate ones, and there are gold and equipment drops. Then you find augmentation which gives you stat multipliers from energy and gold, blood magic which gives you   stuff from energy and gold, advanced training which goes back to giving you multipliers in the   mode, and you need to keep on top of   of this stuff for both modes to keep progression running smoothly. Then there's the prestige system which gives you bonuses primarily based on bosses beaten, training done, blood magic multipliers, and time spent in the run -- with massive penalties for <10 minutes, and massive falloff after 1 hour. This right here more or less solidifies what the game is going for; it wants your attention every   Not that you can go even half an hour before your adventure mode inventory is completely clogged with drops you'll need to sort through before you can get any more. And the equipment isn't even a simple matter of escalating numbers; some gear offers energy   boosts (good for early on), other sets have energy   boosts (good for later), and some have magic boosts instead! There are upgrades you can buy to mitigate   of this micromanagement, though not all of it by a long shot, and they're fairly expensive for how bloody much you'll want them to save you from this madness. I appreciate the absurdity of so many interlocking systems much more as a concept than I do as an engagement conceit. It's a similar sort of metatextual humour to Cookie Clicker, with the key difference being that Cookie Clicker doesn't actually have a series of submenus you need to spelunk through to optimize your PR management or something every time you see a note in the news ticker about how the cookie portals have caused another dough-based tear in reality. Look at the hour counts of all the top positive reviews for this and realize that, as per idle game tradition, it doesn't need to be running to make progress, so it's likely those are mostly   spent managing numbers spreadsheets.", "appid": "1147690", "steamid": "profiles/76561197979724838", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597492800.0}
