{"text": "I bought the original game at release and loved it. I bought this game at release and I regret it. This is not good enough for a full release. Not even close. This should have been an early access game, it is not finished and nowhere near it. Starting with the positive things when compared with the original game: - Holding stations. This is the greatest addition of the game, adding depth to the gameplay and making it feel just complex enough for a seasoned player - High number of foods, restaurants, and chores - Robberies are much more fun, as you can beat the crap out of the robbers rather than having to draw them - Rush hour alerts in advance, giving us enough time to get ready and prep some food to respond to it in the best way possible - Cook for hire mode, which is like the general game but with preset menus, with harder foods as you progress Thumbs up for the artist as the assets look fantastic in general (if we exclude the refried beans and the rice, I can't even describe how terrible the beans look, they don't even fit on top of the nachos properly). I could also list the ability to design your restaurant as a positive, but it is so unintuitive I can't be bothered to actually use it. Which brings me to the list of negatives: - Menu UI. It looks like rushed ♥♥♥♥ and a huge downgrade from CSD1 - Tutorials. On the original game, they were integrated with the campaign, allowing you to feel the general game's mechanics as you play it. CSD2 has 7 different tutorials completely separate from the core game, 4 of which are utterly useless as they're just text. And none of them tells me what I'm supposed to do to run my restaurant. - Talking about campaign, there isn't really one. You have your CSD restaurant, where you can customize the menu, and the other restaurants which are part of the Chef for Hire mode. By the developer's definition, this is a campaign because they're integrated into the same progression system. The campaigns I play usually have stories (not this one). There is no feeling of progression, because you just unlock items (at least I haven't unlocked any relevant stuff so far, all foods are unlocked). There is absolutely no direction on what to do. I know what I can do, but what am I supposed to do? - Emails? Gone. They're supposed to be implemented in the future, but right now they don't exist - Cooking competitions? Gone - Catering events? Gone. Although to be fair, there is a high variety of restaurants which is probably a fair replacement - Achievements?   EDIT: There are now 20 achievements, all with the same icon. There is much more that could be done in this regard and I hope that the dev revisits this in the future. -   EDIT: This has been fixed, though hovering over menu options doesn't always work. -   EDIT: This has been fixed -   EDIT: This has been fixed -   EDIT: This has been fixed - the option is now named \"Start Game\" - Boosters/detractors which alter the gameplay if you do not know them from the original game, are present (according to the developer), but there is no information about it nowhere in the game. There are no options to filter by booster/detractor in a game with over 80 foods in the catalog. There are no search options in a game with over 180 foods in the catalog. - Talking about \"food catalog\", some foods are locked. How to unlock them? By leveling up? By completing certain restaurants? By gaining medals? How would I know, the game doesn't tell me anything. How does my restaurant gain stars? Yeah, no way to know that either. - Unlike in the first game, you're forced to switch pages to apply ingredients in other pages, even when their keybindings are unique - The gold medal requires a perfect day, which is a ridiculous objective when compared with the other medals - Foods feel much more generic. Each food felt unique in CSD1, while in this game everything feels like the same. Also, why would we need brisket slices, turkey slices, ham slices, and sausage slices? They're all sliced meat. They're all holding station foods. They're all entrees. They're all cooked in the similar forms, only being different in pressing a key for seasoning or pressing a key to inject sauce - Chores feel much more generic. The only one having a twist to it is the one where you throw garbage, where you have to repeatedly tap a key to mash the garbage inside This game feels like a barebones framework of what it should really have been. It may become great after an extra year's work on it. But it will also be having deep sales by then, so there's no point on buying it now. The dev's definition of a campaign mode is also ridiculous and one of my biggest gripes with the game. There is nothing relevant to work towards, there is no story to get me hooked. If you're new to this CSD franchise, by all means buy CSD1. It's a fantastic game. It's polished, introduces you properly to the mechanics, has a story, and feels complete. But I can't recommend this game in its current state. This game has none of that. The developer was clearly afraid of delaying the game further (as it was supposed to be released in 2016), which resulted in this precipitated mess of a release. CSD1 is the better game, by far. There is still time to change that, as the potential is present. But at this time, you shouldn't really buy this.", "appid": "386620", "steamid": "profiles/76561198050982821", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "109", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1505390400.0}
