{"text": "A decent pastime game but this game offers nothing new or exciting, and has practically zero replay value. If I was able to I would give a neutral status to this game when it comes to recommendations.   + Decent graphics + Difficulty selection + Automated combat + Clear skill upgrade system - Censorship - Lazy sprite usage - One dimensional characters  ☆☆☆☆☆☆☆★★★  3/10 - Bad  The game looks and feels much like any older JRPG, the character designs are quite nice and just diverse enough from each other. There were several rather creative monster/boss designs, however they had clearly cut corners when it came to sprites and their details. Additionally I find it worth noting that they barely bothered giving art to male characters no matter how important they were to the plot, in fact one such character was the main villain!  As the game begins you are placed in the shoes of a young man who embarks on a journey to escort a self-professed deity to meet with a high priestess. On this journey he is joined by a childhood friend and as it becomes clear that the fate of their world is at stake, the group soon grows and they find themselves battling for their very existence. The plot is simple and offers no surprises yet it is somehow still just enough to keep your mind busy while you go through all the motions. You see every single “shocking” plot twist coming from a mile away because they are simply so cliché, yet it doesn’t really ruin the game. Bigger chances are that the experience may be ruined by the characters themselves; they had the potential to be good characters but failed to be anything but one dimensional caricatures. Their various interactions with each other follow the same script time and time again, only made worse by the fact that naturally all of the party’s ladies have a romantic interest in the only man in their presence. It would be wrong to call the game out on its romance subplots since   but it would surely have fared better without this.  When it comes to the gameplay itself, I found Asdivine Hearts to be very gentle and welcoming to any new players of the genre; it lets you save anywhere you’d like. The menu was clear and all the functions within are easy to navigate. There are quite a few different types of attacks and abilities for all the party members, supporting various types of combat depending on your preferences. The game also understand that grinding can get tiresome and let’s you easily activate automated battle mode, which pretty much guarantees you victories when facing random groups of enemies but will result in a loss against bosses. On the sound side the game is best summarized in one word: monotone. The music is uninspiring and repetitive, but at least the sound effects serve their part decently enough.  Lastly I’ll need to clarify that in my cons I mentioned censorship, but it isn’t a major problem in the game more so than it is just silly modification of this release; there’s a scene where the female characters are bathing and the art of them wearing towels was removed, leaving the place where the art should be simply blank.", "appid": "406110", "steamid": "profiles/76561198319223099", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "7", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1543233600.0}
