{"text": "A monster collecting game with some unique features that make it interesting as well as an occasional innovation on the genre. It stumbles heavily though in multiple areas, most of all being the requirement of grinding.   The overlord is quite similar to Pokemon. The player runs around in the four cardinal directions to move around. Monsters aren’t encountered in tall grass but are instead roaming around freely and will try to run into the player to start a battle. A nice little touch is that monsters will jump over objects to get to the player. The only other real reason to move about the overworld is to get to the various other towns to gain new quests or to finish completed in-progress quests. Monsters can generally be dodged around if that is what a player wants to do, but to catch new monsters the player must battle them. Battles are fun overall, but there are a few aspects of them that make them a bit less enjoyable. The ways that battles take place have the player send out one of their eight different monsters. This is specifically to counter the typing of an opponent.  My personal problem with the typings is that they don’t make sense which makes them hard to memorize. In Pokemon, water beats fire. This gameplay element relates to a real world example that many children know early on. In Monster Crown, the element brute beats the element malicious. This made it difficult for me to make a meaningful mental connection between these concepts. Once a monster is on the field, the player is able to choose from a list of moves that do damage, have effects, or do both. I like that the move list isn’t limited to a small amount of moves as it allows for more strategies. I did dislike that some monsters don’t learn a move of their type for a decent amount of levels. This can mean getting a monster that is good against a certain boss really frustrating. A nitpick I had about the battle UI was that the health bar turned purple upon low health. This kept making me think that my monster was poisoned in some way. Finally, to catch new monsters, the player uses contracts. When a player gets a monster low on health, they can be potentially recruited. This is one aspect that I like and I think has improved upon the Pokemon formula. Based upon how many levels above the monster the player’s monster is and how much health the opponent monster has lost, the catch rate gets points up to five. Each point provides a catch percentage of twenty percent. This makes it much easier for the casual player to figure out the likelihood to catch a monster they want. Unfortunately this information isn’t in the game and is instead on a forum post. I would recommend that the developers mention this with a some lore. Breeding is definitely this game’s strongest mechanic. In the game are over two-hundred creatures that can be caught. Some creatures have great stats while another creature may have the moves that a player likes the most. This is where breeding is important. By breeding these two hypothetical monsters, a baby creature will appear. This baby creature has these combined features, but it also has a semi-unique graphic. Every monster in the game has a version of it based upon the five types in the game. The monster that is the result of breeding will most often inherit the type of its secondary parent. Some creatures do have unique fusions when bred and there are even transformations that can be gained by using items. It is a fun mechanic that provides plenty of ways to play around with it and it is so much fun to see how the monsters the player has bonded with create even more monsters that one already feels like they have a connection to. To gain access to more content, the player has to defeat an overleveled monster. This isn’t so bad for the first boss, but for the bosses after that the levels feel exponentially more powerful instead of additively. This is the main reason that the game requires grinding. The absolute worst part of this game. When I got to the second boss, my monsters were level twelve while the boss monster was level twenty-three. There was a strategy that worked and instead I had to grind. I spent 3 hours grinding and I still only leveled about two or three levels. It was then that I realized that the opponent trainers did the exact thing every time, so I set up a macro and let the game run for additional hours. The game’s tutorial even has the player grinding before they can progress. That really sets the tone of a game and I was desperately hoping that it was a one time occurrence. The story feels really disconnected and all over the place. The player starts out on a farm which isn’t that strange for a monster breeding game. My main issue is then the game has a large story twist and all of the NPCs around the player don’t seem very sad or worried. There is also the issue of a lack of an overarching story early on that provides a storied reason to want to go to future villages. The sound is okay for the moment. It is still missing music and the monster sound effects are a bit basic.  The graphics are nice, especially the pixel art two-dimensional graphics. The graphics remind me quite a bit of Pokemon Gold era graphics. My main issue with the graphics is the color pallete. It is pretty harsh at times and pretty dull other times. Unfortunately, these colors contrast too much which causes the graphics to be less than pleasant to look at. One such example would be the yellow desert that is behind the muted blue and purple NPC sprites. The graphics will be much better if the pallete is a bit retouched. The monster sprites are nice though and fit in well against the battle backdrops. The controls didn’t work wonderfully. I played with a controller and, while the controller is natively supported, some buttons wouldn’t work right. I ended up having to remap most of the keys and then it worked fine. Thus, controls may take some fiddling to get right.  :  Monster Crown was a bit buggy. This mostly was graphical in nature as the game would either suddenly start or stop raining at random moments. This might be tied to the stairs as this bug would mainly occur then. After all of the grinding, this game doesn’t have that much actual content. I played a pre-release version that wasn’t completed so the content took about 14 hours for me to finish.   👍   👍 Fun breeding mechanic 👎   👎 Tons of grinding Poor Graphics Disconnected Story", "appid": "830370", "steamid": "profiles/76561198055780740", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "115", "votes_funny": "8", "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1596196800.0}
