{"text": "A year or so back I purchased the Fatshark Bundle for myself and a friend. At first glance all the games looked entertaining and the reviews were good. Letting the game run for cards it unlocked one achievement and in doing so dropped my overall percentage score, it is because of this that I have played this game a lot sooner than I was planning. Before I get into the details of why you shouldn't purchase this game let me tell you what's good about it first. The game itself looks good and runs smoothly at 60fps. The gladiators/arena remind me of Borderlands with it's wise cracking commentator and post apocalyptic atmosphere. It shares the same universe as Krater, so if you wish to find out more details about this world you can do so if you please. Your character's upgrade system although improperly balanced is fairly fleshed out, allowing for a wide variety of customisation. It's got achievements, trading cards, a cloud save, and cooperative play, all of which work perfectly. Now, for it's shortcomings. The arenas are all more or less the same thing only fashioned into different shapes. You have only a small selection of eight heroes to choose from and roughly fourteen different enemies to kill including optional enemies, bosses, and their spawns. The majority of the skill tree will have to be boosted with a friend because there is no one online and the people who are online will have locked their lobbies, so only their friends can play. The leaderboards are riddled with hackers due to the developers abandoning this game for their newer more popular titles. The upper levels of it's hardest difficulty are impossible to complete even for veterans of the game unless they are completed in a group of four or more, yet another example of poor optimisation. Much like the MMO or current Battle Royale craze Fatshark tried to cash in on the MOBA phase and lost. The atmosphere was nice, the graphics were alright, and the combat was interesting enough, but nothing really stuck out when faced against the other more well developed games such as LoL or Dota 2. In the end Bloodsport.TV is just an egg which the developers cracked before making their omelette which is Vermintide.", "appid": "336420", "steamid": "profiles/76561198067002281", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "28", "votes_funny": "2", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1529323200.0}
{"text": "Ich habe mir doch tatsächlich Mühe gegeben, dem Spiel eine erneute Chance zu bieten.  Kommen wir zu den Ergebnissen: Dank tausender DLC´s zu überteuerten Preisen, die der Qualität von Klopapier entsprechen wurde die ohnehin schon kleine Community (mal abgesehen vom Rank) noch weiter gesplittet. Das Matchmaking System, dass seit Beginn, unabhängig vom eigentlichen Spiel noch nie irgendjemand haben wollte der jemals ein Videospiel anfasste, funktioniert überraschender Weise nicht. Als \"Killer\" habe ich innerhalb von 15 Minuten nicht eine Lobby gefunden. Bzw. es gab keine Survivor welche meinem Host beitraten. Das ganze wiederholte sich 3 mal.  Ohne Erfolg. Der Schaden war angerichtet... Mein Kaffee war kalt also konnte ich ihn wegkippen. Knappe 45 Minuten meiner Lebenszeit bekomme ich nun nicht wieder. Danke dafür. Und genauso wie ich die koffeinhaltige Brühe dem Abfluss hinunter spülte, so tat ich dies im Anschluss mit selbiger Software.  Und da es \"Behaviour Interactive Inc.\" egal ist, so lautet meine Empfehlung: Keine Unterstützung von Entwicklern, die zwar Code schreiben können aber nicht wissen was sie damit anfangen sollen.", "appid": "381210", "steamid": "profiles/76561198001857543", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1473163200.0}
