{"text": "I am changing my previous thumbs up to a very emphatic thumbs down due to recent changes to the game, and the developer's approach to our saves.  In a nutshell, they simply don't give a crap if we have the ability to keep playing.  The save I was working on I had 100 hours invested in, and it is completely lost now.  There is no option to roll back to a prior game version, and the new version trashed all of my resources, vehicles, farm plots, and outposts.  It is essentially a ruined game at this stage, and I have no desire to replay that many hours again to regain what was lost, especially when it could happen all over at any moment.  It was unavoidable, and we were given no warning at all. =============================================== Original Review: While I did recommend the game for playing, that comes with some warnings about shortcomings the game (and it's developer) still have. If you play without downloading custom islands from the Workshop, you're in for a terrible experience - insanely small islands, none of which have any significant abundance of resources to use.  You'll find yourself bouncing around the open ocean in a rubber raft to try and reach others, which as we all know from Castaway is a hugely boneheaded idea. For that reason, DO download one of the larger island packs from the workshop and try to replace most of your vanilla islands.  It will make the game much more enjoyable and less of a continual stress-fest.  I recommend the following pack which I've used extensively in my games: Visuals in Stranded Deep are quite good, as is the progression of skills.  Crafting is interesting, though the backpack is never quite large enough - they really should have implemented different types of craftable backpacks to help the player more in that regard. Underwater environments are just interesting enough to keep the player engaged down there, but they are small and don't have a lot to do from a variety of gameplay perspective. Animals and fish still need fleshing out - there are still too few types to make hunting a fun experience.  Snakes, boars, crabs on land, and a few fish and shark types in the water is about all you can expect. Once you understand what the game can offer (and have replaced most islands in the Cartographer with downloaded workshop islands), you can get started on the meat-and-potatoes of what the game really offers:  raft construction and base construction.  Both are interesting and fun to do, though you'll find yourself spending a lot of time hunting down materials to advance both. Hopefully the development team realizes all the game's shortcomings and will work to add additional content and systems.  If they release in less than ~2 years (given the terribly slow state of progress it's had), they're selling it short.  At that point I'd change my review to thumbs down.  Their most recent focus has been porting to consoles, which comes as a deep disappointment to most PC gamers on Steam.  The game needs a lot more work, and yet it seems like the developer is going for a cash grab by taking PC Early Access funds and using them for cross-platform development. tldr;  Thumbs up and recommended only if using islands from the Workshop.  Game still needs a *lot* more content and development, but can be fun when you realize it's still in Early Access, and \"you get what you get\" from where it is currently.", "appid": "313120", "steamid": "profiles/76561197970676861", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1594296000.0}
