{"text": "Symphony is an interesting game that turns your music into a game much like Beat Hazard. I’ve played Beat Hazard to death, Gradius, R-Type and other games of the SHMUP genre and I imagined Symphony would be just as awesome, but it didn’t live up to my expectations. The gameplay starts with the easiest difficulty and you climb your way up. Within each level you kill ships of various forms that move according to the music. The faster the beat, the faster the enemy ships but the more score you can get. As you defeat bosses and unlock more pieces of the Symphony of Souls, you unlock more enemies as well as additional changes to earn more inspiration and kudos (currencies used to buy ship guns and upgrades). Each song has one hidden weapon or perk that is revealed once the song is finished. Upon beating the song, one has the opportunity to buy it at that point or later. The player ship has four gun slots that can be customized to the player’s preference. Controls are simple and there is no death (not finishing the song) but one might not get any rewards.  However, thanks to the above SHMUP games I’ve played before, there are some things that I expect that don’t happen or aren’t logical in the game. Others might find some of these quirks desirable and enjoyable but sadly I don’t. Some of these I can work around while others are just plain frustrating.  So personally I wouldn’t recommend it, but if it’s your cup of tea you may enjoy it. Here are the quirks that I don’t like. One example is if you play a harder difficulty, you should get more inspiration and kudos. However, the amount of inspiration you get decreases after the third difficulty, and I can only wonder if the hardest difficulty gives you even more  than the third. On the other hand, you do get crazy amount of kudos which, while nice, isn’t needed too much in upgrades. By playing enough songs to get to the fifth difficulty, I accumulated more kudos than I seemed to need, making the harder difficulties only worth it for score and not for resources. Boss unlocks still happen at lower difficulties which makes sense, for those that aren’t good with the genre. Ship parts seem to consist of mainly subwoofers (guns that fire to the beat of the music), shotguns, and the occasional rocket launcher. One unlocks the ability to buy a single gun or perk that appears when a song is beaten. While these guns are better than nothing, the guns I want, double guns, seem to be far and few between. One might assume this isn’t a problem once the ship is loaded the way you want, but unfortunately it is. Given each difficulty, you get a score multiplier, determined by the attack volley total of your guns. As the difficulty increases, the strength of the guns can increase without having the multiplier dip below 1. Because guns can’t be de-leveled, this leads to a perplexing problem. If I play at a higher difficulty and switch down, I’m too strong so I can only equip one or two of the guns. Given the gameplay mechanics, if I get hit in that spot I lose the gun until I can pick up another note, which without guns is very hard to do. With multiple weaker guns, I can take a hit but I can’t de-level. There’s no store either, so I’m left with lots of crappy guns I can buy that I probably don’t want to use, or I end up using only one good gun. For now I have the invincibility and bomb perks which make me invincible for a few seconds so I can melee ships (for no musical note) and create an explosion that takes out a good chunk of the screen, respectively. My main issues are the inability to store bombs, and bombs that kill the user. For the first issue, bombs are sometimes dropped when you kill a chain of enemies. The problem is that I might just run into the bomb, because I want the musical note that the enemy dropped. However, the bomb activates as soon as I touch it, so this leads to a waste of a bomb. Worse yet is when the bomb spawns on the spawn point and I hit it once I spawn. Bombs might not even spawn at the most useful times, forcing the player to evade the item if they want to avoid using it, leading to a weird play style of avoiding powerups. Similar issues exist for the invincibility so I wish there was a way to store it, as oppose to littering the screen and avoiding stuff. If nothing else, make the bomb smaller and possibly force the user to stay on it for a second, as opposed to just activating on impact.  For the second issue, a bomb grants no invincibility. However, there is one type of enemy which explodes on impact. This leads to one’s death if one runs into a bomb while this enemy is close, creating another powerup-related problem. Shots are not destroyed, making it difficult to evade if one doesn’t notice the shot fired just before they die. In rarer cases, I’ve gotten four bombs in a row and getting one would kill me, limiting my motion. Related to this issue is that score does NOT increase unless one picks up notes.  Because of this, at harder difficulties the game turns into running into the crowd just to get notes. Some of the comments above exist because this game doesn’t follow the norm, and it is indeed a fallacy to assume that games should follow the norm. However, at least give me the ability to downgrade weapons and logically make it so that harder difficulty results in both more kudos AND more inspiration. A weapon store or at least a preview ability to know what I will unlock would be nice. Possibly give me a store too and a smaller ship hit box, but that might be asking too much. Despite all the ranting and blocks of text, it is a beautiful game with awesome boss fights that show up and create a story about your music. Customizing ships with different guns is an excellent feature that some games might overlook, although it can make the game really easy too. Moving with the beat and shooting enemies is always fun, but can also be annoying in strange ways due to the above. Yet, that’s always not a bad thing.  Perhaps I’m too used to certain things existing in this genre, but that’s how I roll. In all likelihood I’ll get to the last difficulty and stop. EDIT 1:Another issue I've found is the lack of audio cues for when invinciblity will fade. This leads to the rare, ram into your death scenario which rarely helps considering how there's roughly a five to ten second delay penality for getting a new ship.", "appid": "207750", "steamid": "profiles/76561198025839480", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1397304000.0}
