{"text": "The one word I would use to describe this game is frustrating. The gameplay was frustrating, the mechanics were frustrating, the story was frustrating, and everything about this game just frustrated me. The mechanics are quite simple - it's based around momentum and speed. However the way it works in practice creates a system where half the time jumps that look like they should be made are not made and stupid stuff that shouldn't work end up working. Half the game when I was stuck at a part I was jumping around like a lunatic grabbing on to anything I could. The actual running is decent but takes a while to get used to when you're used to most games having a dedicated run button on the shift key I ended up ducking a lot at the beginning when trying to speed up. The running also doesn't feel as fast as I think it should. The fighting has been talked about in length so I won’t discuss it much here but I can say that trying to fight enemies is annoying and involves clicking wildly until you finish them off. Honestly I think it comes down to the physics engine of the game - it just doesn't work for this type of game or any game for that matter. The gameplay is annoying. The game is advertised as a running parkour never stop action packed game but it takes every opportunity to slow down your character. This is especially noticed in the later levels where they introduce more enemies and \"puzzles\". The game is cryptic as ♥♥♥♥ - even with the red markers trying to show you where to go. There were many moments where I was stuck in one small room looking around and jumping trying to find where to go. It seems linear but half the solutions don't feel like the actually solutions because they involve doing weird jumps and wall climbs. The landing after a jump is also super weird and it takes a bit to get the timing right but by the end of the game I was getting it mostly consistently so I have to give it credit there. Sliding slows down your speed about 90% of the time and it just doesn't feel good to slide in the game. Then the enemies. I honestly have no idea why they thought it was a good idea to put actual enemies in the game. Ones that you have to stop and fight along the way and which takes longer to fight thanks to the ♥♥♥♥♥♥ combat. I can't comment much on the story since I mostly skipped it because of the boring and jarring cut scenes that take place between levels. You will probably do the same if you play this game. The person talking in your ear is annoying as well. \"What are you doing Faith!?\" \"Get out of there Faith!\" - These are comments you will hear constantly. I swear the guy only recorded 3 voice lines. Overall, the game had me yelling at my screen and wanting to smash my mouse with how frustrating everything about this game is. I would honestly not recommend this game to anyone and don't understand why so many people enjoy this game. I wish I could like this game but IMO it seems like a bad case of great idea and terrible execution. Save your money.", "appid": "17410", "steamid": "profiles/76561198013103841", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1521115200.0}
{"text": "I want to love DisHonored 2. I really, really do. But it took the problem the first one had, and instead of   that problem, they went and made it  That problem is the \"vaunted\" Chaos system. The system that turns your character into a monster, makes others call them a monster, etc, if you kill people. The makers of this game really,   need to learn the meaning of the phrase \"justifiable homocide,\" because seldom in a videogame is homocide more justifiable than on Mission 1 of DisHonored 2. So, I did just that, for story reasons, and took out   the hostiles on Mission 1... And apparently the game is now locked to High Chaos, I'm being forced to play someone who talks like an absolute  , and it's awful. This is not the story I want to be playing. But I'm 33 freaking hours in again. Oh, and the game is very bad about giving you \"credit\" for kills you had nothing to do with, too. I don't want to spend another hundred hours with Quicksave and Quickload bound to Mouse1 and Mouse 2, checking my game stats after each encounter to ensure I didn't accidently rack up a kill, playing the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ game  . Despite taking   the \"nice\" story options, I'm still at High Chaos, and the game is constantly telling me I'm a monster. At this point, I'm ready to use CheatEngine to force the game to record 0 kills and detections and give myself infinite health and just run through the game overtly slaughtering everyone in my path, just to see the good storyline in a reasonable timeframe.", "appid": "403640", "steamid": "profiles/76561197968413283", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1483531200.0}
